00:07:20.500 --> 00:07:23.670
So, let's start with talking
about photoelectron

00:07:23.670 --> 00:07:27.010
spectroscopy.

00:07:27.010 --> 00:07:29.820
This actually relates very
closely to what we discussed

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:33.510
in class on Friday before the
long weekend, and what we were

00:07:33.510 --> 00:07:37.710
talking about is the energy
levels of multielectron atoms.

00:07:37.710 --> 00:07:40.440
So what we'll start with today
is talking about the technique

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:43.570
that's primarily used to
actually experimentally figure

00:07:43.570 --> 00:07:45.960
out what these different
energy levels are.

00:07:45.960 --> 00:07:47.340
And this is called photoelectron
spectroscopy,

00:07:47.340 --> 00:07:51.960
and essentially what it is is
very similar conceptually to

00:07:51.960 --> 00:07:54.710
what we were talking about way
back in the first couple

00:07:54.710 --> 00:07:56.120
lectures when we were
talking about the

00:07:56.120 --> 00:07:57.640
photoelectric effect.

00:07:57.640 --> 00:08:01.270
Because here what we have is
some atom that we're studying,

00:08:01.270 --> 00:08:04.900
in the case, it's going to be
a gas, and we hit it with a

00:08:04.900 --> 00:08:07.550
photon that has some
incident energy.

00:08:07.550 --> 00:08:11.590
So e sub i, some energy that the
photon comes in with, and

00:08:11.590 --> 00:08:14.620
if it has sufficient energy to
eject an electron, it will do

00:08:14.620 --> 00:08:18.210
that, and our electron will be
ejected with a certain kinetic

00:08:18.210 --> 00:08:21.000
energy, which is going to be
whatever energy is left over

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:24.200
from the initial energy we put
in minus what was taken up in

00:08:24.200 --> 00:08:27.370
order to actually ionize
or eject the electron.

00:08:27.370 --> 00:08:29.670
So, you can see how this can
directly give us different

00:08:29.670 --> 00:08:32.050
ionization energies for
any atom that we're

00:08:32.050 --> 00:08:33.460
interested in studying.

00:08:33.460 --> 00:08:35.880
For example, with neon we can
think about all of the

00:08:35.880 --> 00:08:38.490
different orbital energies
we could be looking at.

00:08:38.490 --> 00:08:40.520
In the first case, so
here is the electron

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:42.390
configuration of neon.

00:08:42.390 --> 00:08:45.880
So we can think about what
is our most loosely-bound

00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:49.065
electron, what's that highest
energy orbital, and it's going

00:08:49.065 --> 00:08:51.500
to be the 2 p orbital,
that's going to be

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:52.610
what's highest in energy.

00:08:52.610 --> 00:08:55.570
So if we're going to eject an
electron using a minimum

00:08:55.570 --> 00:08:58.130
amount of energy, that's where
it's going to come from.

00:08:58.130 --> 00:09:00.470
So, you can imagine, that we'll
actually probably have a

00:09:00.470 --> 00:09:03.890
lot of kinetic energy left over
if we put a lot of energy

00:09:03.890 --> 00:09:04.790
in in the first place.

00:09:04.790 --> 00:09:07.340
We're only using up a little
bit to eject the electron,

00:09:07.340 --> 00:09:09.480
then we'll have a
lot left over.

00:09:09.480 --> 00:09:10.990
So, one difference between
photoelectron spectroscopy

00:09:10.990 --> 00:09:14.760
and, for example, the
photoelectric effect is that

00:09:14.760 --> 00:09:17.250
in this case, we're not just
looking at one energy level,

00:09:17.250 --> 00:09:19.330
which is what we were looking
at from the surface of a

00:09:19.330 --> 00:09:22.530
metal, now we're talking about
this gaseous atom.

00:09:22.530 --> 00:09:26.470
So we can actually pop an
electron or eject an electron

00:09:26.470 --> 00:09:29.720
from any single orbital that is
occupied within the atom.

00:09:29.720 --> 00:09:33.180
So, for example, it's not just
the 2 p that we could actually

00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:35.380
take an electron from, we
could also think about

00:09:35.380 --> 00:09:38.190
ejecting an electron from
the 2 s orbital.

00:09:38.190 --> 00:09:40.460
Now this, of course, is going to
take more energy because a

00:09:40.460 --> 00:09:43.610
2 s is lower, it has has a more
negative binding energy

00:09:43.610 --> 00:09:46.670
than the 2 p, but that's OK as
long as we put in enough

00:09:46.670 --> 00:09:49.470
energy, but what we're going to
find is the kinetic energy

00:09:49.470 --> 00:09:52.450
coming out with the electron
is actually going to be a

00:09:52.450 --> 00:09:55.090
little bit less, right, because
we had to use up more

00:09:55.090 --> 00:09:57.280
energy to eject the electron,
so we don't have

00:09:57.280 --> 00:10:00.090
as much left over.

00:10:00.090 --> 00:10:02.540
There's actually one more
orbital that we could talk

00:10:02.540 --> 00:10:05.430
about if we're talking about
this sample case of neon,

00:10:05.430 --> 00:10:09.470
which is a 1 s orbital, and if
we're talking about a 1 s

00:10:09.470 --> 00:10:13.030
orbital, now we're going to be
even lower in energy still, so

00:10:13.030 --> 00:10:16.440
that means the minimum energy
required to eject an electron

00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:19.320
is going to be at its highest,
so that means the energy that

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:22.200
we have left over that turns
into kinetic energy for the

00:10:22.200 --> 00:10:26.000
electron, is now going to
be really quite small.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:30.760
And what happens when you
irradiate one of these atoms

00:10:30.760 --> 00:10:34.290
that you're studying with this
light is in photoelectron

00:10:34.290 --> 00:10:36.350
spectroscopy, you want to make
sure that you put in enough

00:10:36.350 --> 00:10:40.180
energy to actually ionize any
single electron that you have

00:10:40.180 --> 00:10:41.000
in the atom.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.270
So the way that we really make
sure this is done is that we

00:10:43.270 --> 00:10:44.710
use x-rays.

00:10:44.710 --> 00:10:48.200
So you know that x-rays are
higher frequency than UV

00:10:48.200 --> 00:10:51.020
light, for example, that means
it's also higher energy than

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:54.880
UV light, and if you think
back to our photoelectric

00:10:54.880 --> 00:10:57.465
effect experiments, do you
remember what type of light we

00:10:57.465 --> 00:10:58.930
were usually using for those?

00:10:58.930 --> 00:11:01.490
Does anyone remember?

00:11:01.490 --> 00:11:02.620
Yeah.

00:11:02.620 --> 00:11:04.560
It was UV light that we used.

00:11:04.560 --> 00:11:06.850
Well, we can't guarantee with
UV light we'll have enough

00:11:06.850 --> 00:11:09.450
energy to eject every single
electron, so that's why when

00:11:09.450 --> 00:11:12.500
we use x-rays, they're higher
energy, you can pretty much be

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:14.000
guaranteed we're going
to eject all of

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.160
those electrons there.

00:11:17.160 --> 00:11:19.960
So I said that this technique
was used to experimentally

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:22.580
determine what the different
binding energies or the

00:11:22.580 --> 00:11:25.730
different ionization energies
are for the different states

00:11:25.730 --> 00:11:27.400
in a multielectron atom.

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:29.140
Another way to say
states is to talk

00:11:29.140 --> 00:11:30.650
about different orbitals.

00:11:30.650 --> 00:11:33.410
So we can do this directly as
long as we have certain types

00:11:33.410 --> 00:11:34.140
of information.

00:11:34.140 --> 00:11:37.130
The first that we need to know
the energy of the photon

00:11:37.130 --> 00:11:41.030
that's incident on
our gaseous atom.

00:11:41.030 --> 00:11:43.590
The second piece of information
we need to know is

00:11:43.590 --> 00:11:46.320
what actually the kinetic
energy is of the ejected

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:48.490
electron, and that's something
we can just measure by

00:11:48.490 --> 00:11:50.470
measuring its velocity.

00:11:50.470 --> 00:11:53.980
So we can use an equation to
relate the incident energy and

00:11:53.980 --> 00:11:56.570
the kinetic energy to the
ionization energy, or the

00:11:56.570 --> 00:11:58.820
energy that's required
to eject an electron.

00:11:58.820 --> 00:12:01.140
This should all sound incredibly
familiar, like I'm

00:12:01.140 --> 00:12:03.780
just repeating myself in terms
of photoelectric effect,

00:12:03.780 --> 00:12:06.010
because essentially that's what
I'm doing, and that's one

00:12:06.010 --> 00:12:08.680
reason we spent so much time
and did so many problem-set

00:12:08.680 --> 00:12:10.760
problems on the photoelectric
effect.

00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:13.640
So what we're saying here is
the incident energy, so the

00:12:13.640 --> 00:12:17.230
energy coming in, is just equal
to the minimum energy

00:12:17.230 --> 00:12:19.420
that's required to a
eject an electron.

00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:21.580
When we talked about the
photoelectric effect, that was

00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:22.660
called the work function.

00:12:22.660 --> 00:12:25.970
In this case, it's called the
ionization energy, plus

00:12:25.970 --> 00:12:27.860
whatever kinetic energy we have

00:12:27.860 --> 00:12:29.810
left over in the electron.

00:12:29.810 --> 00:12:32.480
So if we want to solve for
ionization energy, we can just

00:12:32.480 --> 00:12:33.980
rearrange this equation.

00:12:33.980 --> 00:12:36.700
Our ionization energy is going
to be equal to the incident

00:12:36.700 --> 00:12:39.010
energy coming in, minus
the kinetic

00:12:39.010 --> 00:12:40.060
energy of the electron.

00:12:40.060 --> 00:12:43.810
So, let's take a look at the
different kinetic energies

00:12:43.810 --> 00:12:47.500
that would be observed in a
spectrum for neon where we had

00:12:47.500 --> 00:12:49.330
this incident energy here.

00:12:49.330 --> 00:12:51.560
And it turns out that the first
kinetic energy that we

00:12:51.560 --> 00:12:55.030
would see or the highest kinetic
energy, would be 12 32

00:12:55.030 --> 00:12:56.800
electron volts.

00:12:56.800 --> 00:13:00.080
So if that's the case doing a
quick little calculation, what

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:03.800
would the ionization energy be
for a 2 p electron in neon?

00:13:03.800 --> 00:13:07.650
Yup, 22.

00:13:07.650 --> 00:13:12.560
So, basically all we did was
take 12 54, subtract 12 32,

00:13:12.560 --> 00:13:15.250
and we got 22 electron volts.

00:13:15.250 --> 00:13:17.050
We can do the same thing
for the other

00:13:17.050 --> 00:13:18.010
observed kinetic energy.

00:13:18.010 --> 00:13:22.250
So, for example, in the second
case, we say that we see 12 06

00:13:22.250 --> 00:13:24.140
in terms of the kinetic
energy.

00:13:24.140 --> 00:13:26.430
Same sort of subtraction
problem, what do we have for

00:13:26.430 --> 00:13:30.100
the ionization energy
of the 2 s electron?

00:13:30.100 --> 00:13:30.980
Good, quick math.

00:13:30.980 --> 00:13:32.230
All right, so 48
electron volts.

00:13:32.230 --> 00:13:35.430
And let's look at the final
kinetic energy that we'd

00:13:35.430 --> 00:13:38.720
observe in this spectrum, which
is 384 electron volts,

00:13:38.720 --> 00:13:40.110
so what is that third

00:13:40.110 --> 00:13:44.810
corresponding ionization energy?

00:13:44.810 --> 00:13:47.260
I couldn't quite hear, but I
have a feeling everyone said

00:13:47.260 --> 00:13:50.460
870 electron volts.

00:13:50.460 --> 00:13:54.150
So, we can actually kind of
visualize what we would see if

00:13:54.150 --> 00:13:56.640
we were looking at a
photoelectron spectrum.

00:13:56.640 --> 00:13:59.220
And what we would see if we were
graphing, for example,

00:13:59.220 --> 00:14:02.600
increasing kinetic energy,
is we would see 1 line

00:14:02.600 --> 00:14:06.570
corresponding to each of these
energies of electrons that we

00:14:06.570 --> 00:14:07.680
see coming out.

00:14:07.680 --> 00:14:10.190
And, of course, each of those
electrons correspond to an

00:14:10.190 --> 00:14:13.300
electron coming out of
a particular orbital.

00:14:13.300 --> 00:14:18.180
So in the case of 12 32, that is
our highest kinetic energy,

00:14:18.180 --> 00:14:21.040
that means it's our lowest
ionization energy -- it's the

00:14:21.040 --> 00:14:24.140
smallest amount of energy it
takes to pop an electron out

00:14:24.140 --> 00:14:25.100
of that orbital.

00:14:25.100 --> 00:14:29.770
So that's why we see the 2 p
here, the 2 s is 12 06, and it

00:14:29.770 --> 00:14:33.130
makes sense that what we see
as the greatest ionization

00:14:33.130 --> 00:14:36.350
energy, which is also the
smallest kinetic energy is

00:14:36.350 --> 00:14:37.600
that 1 s orbital.

00:14:37.600 --> 00:14:40.130
Remember, because that 1 s
orbital is all the way down in

00:14:40.130 --> 00:14:42.310
terms of if we're thinking about
an energy diagram, we're

00:14:42.310 --> 00:14:45.210
all the way down here, so we
have a huge amount of energy

00:14:45.210 --> 00:14:49.120
we have to put into the system
in order to eject an electron.

00:14:49.120 --> 00:14:51.130
So what I want to point out when
you're kind of looking at

00:14:51.130 --> 00:14:53.920
these numbers here, what the
significance is, look at that

00:14:53.920 --> 00:14:56.850
huge difference between what
the ionization energies are

00:14:56.850 --> 00:15:00.160
for what we call those valence
electrons, those outer shell

00:15:00.160 --> 00:15:03.460
electrons, versus the ionization
energy for the 1 s

00:15:03.460 --> 00:15:06.390
orbital -- those are core
electrons there.

00:15:06.390 --> 00:15:08.620
So we can think about something
I mentioned last

00:15:08.620 --> 00:15:10.560
time, which is when we're
thinking about chemistry and

00:15:10.560 --> 00:15:13.560
what's really interesting in
terms of chemical reactions,

00:15:13.560 --> 00:15:15.880
it's mostly valence electrons
we're talking about, those are

00:15:15.880 --> 00:15:16.750
the ones that tend to be

00:15:16.750 --> 00:15:18.660
involved in chemical reactions.

00:15:18.660 --> 00:15:21.000
It makes a lot of sense when we
look at it energetically,

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:24.955
because if we think about a 1 s
core electron, that's going

00:15:24.955 --> 00:15:27.060
to be held really, really
tightly to the nucleus.

00:15:27.060 --> 00:15:29.440
We see that we have to put
this huge energy in to

00:15:29.440 --> 00:15:33.410
actually get a 1 s electron
ejected, so it makes a lot of

00:15:33.410 --> 00:15:35.640
sense that we wouldn't want to
pay that energy cost in a

00:15:35.640 --> 00:15:37.190
normal chemical reaction.

00:15:37.190 --> 00:15:40.690
And we don't -- we very rarely
would see these core electrons

00:15:40.690 --> 00:15:44.610
actually being involved in
any type of a reaction.

00:15:44.610 --> 00:15:47.600
All right, so one thing that I
want to point out, which I

00:15:47.600 --> 00:15:49.990
said many, many times on Friday,
and this is perhaps

00:15:49.990 --> 00:15:52.990
the last time I'll say it, but
one last time is we can think

00:15:52.990 --> 00:15:56.530
about why we only see a line for
the 2 p orbital, versus we

00:15:56.530 --> 00:16:00.750
don't see separate lines for a
2 p x, a 2 p y, and a 2 p z.

00:16:00.750 --> 00:16:03.450
Remember, we need those three
quantum numbers to completely

00:16:03.450 --> 00:16:04.620
describe the orbital.

00:16:04.620 --> 00:16:06.870
Why do we just see one
for all the p's?

00:16:06.870 --> 00:16:09.650
And the reason is that the
energy of the orbitals, depend

00:16:09.650 --> 00:16:12.520
on two quantum numbers, and
that's quantum number n, and

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:13.740
quantum number l.

00:16:13.740 --> 00:16:16.620
M does not actually have an
effect, in this case, on the

00:16:16.620 --> 00:16:18.350
energy of the orbital.

00:16:18.350 --> 00:16:20.100
So that's why we're not
seeing separate

00:16:20.100 --> 00:16:24.370
lines in this spectrum.

00:16:24.370 --> 00:16:24.600
All right.

00:16:24.600 --> 00:16:28.300
So let's go ahead and try an
example here in thinking about

00:16:28.300 --> 00:16:29.770
photoelectron spectroscopy.

00:16:29.770 --> 00:16:33.120
So, let's say we're looking at
an element and we have an

00:16:33.120 --> 00:16:35.950
emission spectra, and we know
that it has five distinct

00:16:35.950 --> 00:16:38.860
different kinetic energies
in that spectrum.

00:16:38.860 --> 00:16:42.600
We might be asked, for example,
to determine what all

00:16:42.600 --> 00:16:44.740
of the different elements could
be that would produce a

00:16:44.740 --> 00:16:47.410
spectrum that gave us
5 different lines.

00:16:47.410 --> 00:16:49.620
So the first thing that we want
to do, if we're thinking

00:16:49.620 --> 00:16:56.210
about something like this, is
just to determine exactly what

00:16:56.210 --> 00:16:58.990
orbitals are causing the five
different lines that we're

00:16:58.990 --> 00:17:00.690
seeing in the spectrum.

00:17:00.690 --> 00:17:03.060
So, if we're talking about five
different orbitals and

00:17:03.060 --> 00:17:05.420
we're talking about a ground
state atom, we know that we

00:17:05.420 --> 00:17:06.880
just need to start
at the bottom and

00:17:06.880 --> 00:17:08.220
work our way out up.

00:17:08.220 --> 00:17:10.840
So, our first orbital that an
electron must be coming from

00:17:10.840 --> 00:17:11.900
is the 1 s.

00:17:11.900 --> 00:17:13.583
What comes after that?

00:17:13.583 --> 00:17:15.190
2 s.

00:17:15.190 --> 00:17:16.070
All right, then what?

00:17:16.070 --> 00:17:20.740
2 p.

00:17:20.740 --> 00:17:22.540
After that?

00:17:22.540 --> 00:17:23.990
3 s.

00:17:23.990 --> 00:17:25.530
Next?

00:17:25.530 --> 00:17:31.890
3 p, and that's 1, 2, 3, 4 --
that gives us five different

00:17:31.890 --> 00:17:34.200
options, five different
orbitals, five different

00:17:34.200 --> 00:17:35.820
energies right there.

00:17:35.820 --> 00:17:38.950
So, then all we need to do to
determine which elements that

00:17:38.950 --> 00:17:41.960
corresponds to is take a look
at our periodic table.

00:17:41.960 --> 00:17:45.490
So we want to look at any
element that has a 3 p orbital

00:17:45.490 --> 00:17:49.470
filled, but that does not then
go on and have a 4 s, because

00:17:49.470 --> 00:17:51.880
if it had the 4 s filled then
we would actually see six

00:17:51.880 --> 00:17:53.360
lines in the spectrum.

00:17:53.360 --> 00:17:58.230
So that is relevant for all
of these atoms here, so we

00:17:58.230 --> 00:18:00.840
actually have several different
possibilities.

00:18:00.840 --> 00:18:06.250
It could be aluminum, silicone,
phosphorous, sulfur,

00:18:06.250 --> 00:18:09.530
chlorine or argon.

00:18:09.530 --> 00:18:12.000
Any one of these different
elements could actually

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:16.410
produce a photoelectron
spectroscopy spectrum that has

00:18:16.410 --> 00:18:18.090
five distinct lines.

00:18:18.090 --> 00:18:20.950
If I went on and told you what
the different incident light

00:18:20.950 --> 00:18:24.830
was, and what the electrons were
ejected with, and then

00:18:24.830 --> 00:18:26.910
you could look up the ionization
energy for the

00:18:26.910 --> 00:18:29.780
particular different elements,
you should be able to actually

00:18:29.780 --> 00:18:32.450
determine exactly which element
it is, but just with

00:18:32.450 --> 00:18:34.830
the information given, we can
only narrow it down to these

00:18:34.830 --> 00:18:36.880
choices here.

00:18:36.880 --> 00:18:41.350
So let's actually let you try
another example of solving a

00:18:41.350 --> 00:18:43.540
problem that has to do with
one of the spectrums. So,

00:18:43.540 --> 00:18:46.700
let's turn to another clicker
question here.

