00:20:52.030 --> 00:20:52.870
All right.

00:20:52.870 --> 00:20:55.750
So let's turn our attention to a
new topic, which is thinking

00:20:55.750 --> 00:20:58.300
a little bit about the periodic
table, and also

00:20:58.300 --> 00:21:00.000
talking about periodic trends.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:03.140
And there's a lot we can explain
by talking about what

00:21:03.140 --> 00:21:06.220
we see in the periodic table
in terms of what different

00:21:06.220 --> 00:21:08.050
trends are in grouping
different elements in

00:21:08.050 --> 00:21:10.860
different spots within
the periodic table.

00:21:10.860 --> 00:21:13.840
So, here we have a picture of
Dmitri Mendeleev, who is one

00:21:13.840 --> 00:21:17.220
of the scientists responsible
for first compiling the

00:21:17.220 --> 00:21:18.560
periodic table.

00:21:18.560 --> 00:21:21.830
You'll notice I have what's a
very flattering picture of him

00:21:21.830 --> 00:21:24.860
up here, and if you haven't done
the reading yet you might

00:21:24.860 --> 00:21:27.130
not think this is particularly
flattering, but if you look at

00:21:27.130 --> 00:21:31.130
the picture of him in the book,
you'll notice I chose a

00:21:31.130 --> 00:21:34.820
very flattering picture of
Dmitri up here, and here he's

00:21:34.820 --> 00:21:37.450
pondering putting these
elements together in a

00:21:37.450 --> 00:21:38.690
periodic table.

00:21:38.690 --> 00:21:42.790
And he actually did this in the
late 1800's, back before

00:21:42.790 --> 00:21:45.690
even all of the elements that we
know today were discovered,

00:21:45.690 --> 00:21:49.740
really only about 60% or so, 70%
were discovered then that

00:21:49.740 --> 00:21:51.040
we now know today.

00:21:51.040 --> 00:21:55.230
But still, he was able to put
together a periodic table.

00:21:55.230 --> 00:21:57.870
And what he did what he actually
grouped things in

00:21:57.870 --> 00:22:00.080
terms of their chemical
properties.

00:22:00.080 --> 00:22:02.550
So the way that we like to
think of things now is in

00:22:02.550 --> 00:22:04.660
terms of electron
configurations, right, but at

00:22:04.660 --> 00:22:06.760
the time that wasn't
really understood.

00:22:06.760 --> 00:22:09.240
So, instead, it was amazing he
was able to group things in

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:11.390
terms of the properties
that he saw.

00:22:11.390 --> 00:22:15.050
So, for example, if he was
talking about the group one

00:22:15.050 --> 00:22:18.040
metals, lithium, sodium,
potassium -- he noticed these

00:22:18.040 --> 00:22:20.140
were all very soft reactive
metals, those

00:22:20.140 --> 00:22:21.540
were grouped together.

00:22:21.540 --> 00:22:26.000
Versus looking at, for example,
helium or neon or

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.910
argon, these are all inert
gases, inert meaning

00:22:28.910 --> 00:22:32.280
essentially do not react, those
were grouped together in

00:22:32.280 --> 00:22:33.850
the periodic table.

00:22:33.850 --> 00:22:37.070
So basically, at the time he
was just going on size and

00:22:37.070 --> 00:22:41.050
then traits, but what we
actually know today is that we

00:22:41.050 --> 00:22:45.130
can also order things in the
periodic table by electron

00:22:45.130 --> 00:22:45.750
configuration.

00:22:45.750 --> 00:22:48.130
In fact, that is the most
logical way for us

00:22:48.130 --> 00:22:49.300
to look at it now.

00:22:49.300 --> 00:22:51.700
So, for example, if we're
actually thinking about

00:22:51.700 --> 00:22:54.150
electron configuration and we
look at lithium, sodium and

00:22:54.150 --> 00:22:58.060
potassium, these all have
one valence electron.

00:22:58.060 --> 00:23:01.420
So basically, that means one
electron in an s orbital in

00:23:01.420 --> 00:23:03.060
their outer-most most shell.

00:23:03.060 --> 00:23:05.740
So that explains why they're so
reactive, they're all very

00:23:05.740 --> 00:23:08.510
willing to give up that 1 s
orbital and then drop to a

00:23:08.510 --> 00:23:10.280
lower energy level.

00:23:10.280 --> 00:23:14.690
In contrast, helium, neon, and
argon all have filled shells.

00:23:14.690 --> 00:23:17.140
That also explains why
they're very stable.

00:23:17.140 --> 00:23:19.480
They're not going to want to
add on another electron,

00:23:19.480 --> 00:23:21.950
because then it'll have to jump
a very large energy level

00:23:21.950 --> 00:23:24.820
and start filling in another
shell -- go from n equals 2,

00:23:24.820 --> 00:23:29.370
to n equals 3, and n equals
4, and so on.

00:23:29.370 --> 00:23:31.760
So it turns out that we can
really know a lot just by

00:23:31.760 --> 00:23:34.430
looking at the periodic table.

00:23:34.430 --> 00:23:37.070
You will never in this class
have to memorize anything

00:23:37.070 --> 00:23:38.070
about the periodic table.

00:23:38.070 --> 00:23:40.150
Depending on what kind of
chemistry you go in to, you

00:23:40.150 --> 00:23:43.120
might accidentally memorize
parts of the table, which is

00:23:43.120 --> 00:23:45.710
fine, but what you really want
to know how to do is know how

00:23:45.710 --> 00:23:48.110
to use the periodic table.

00:23:48.110 --> 00:23:51.160
But you actually need to keep
a few caveats in mind as you

00:23:51.160 --> 00:23:54.330
do this, which is the fact that
trends predict a lot of

00:23:54.330 --> 00:23:57.490
chemical properties, but they
can't predict everything in

00:23:57.490 --> 00:23:59.460
terms of biological
properties.

00:23:59.460 --> 00:24:02.370
And after the periodic table
was developed in the late

00:24:02.370 --> 00:24:04.760
1800's, people didn't understand
this quite as well,

00:24:04.760 --> 00:24:06.170
they took things a little
more literally.

00:24:06.170 --> 00:24:09.340
They thought, for example, if
you could do something with

00:24:09.340 --> 00:24:12.250
one element, if you looked at
an element very close to it,

00:24:12.250 --> 00:24:14.400
it would be similar enough that
you could maybe replace

00:24:14.400 --> 00:24:15.400
it with that.

00:24:15.400 --> 00:24:18.120
Today we know, for example, if
you can put one certain kind

00:24:18.120 --> 00:24:21.030
of element in your mouth
or eat that, it doesn't

00:24:21.030 --> 00:24:23.160
necessarily mean you want to put
the element next to it and

00:24:23.160 --> 00:24:25.740
your mouth as well, that
might not be safe.

00:24:25.740 --> 00:24:29.390
But this is things we've learned
as the years have gone

00:24:29.390 --> 00:24:30.370
past.

00:24:30.370 --> 00:24:33.840
So, let's just take a quick
example to show how not

00:24:33.840 --> 00:24:36.050
completely you can use these
periodic trends, that there

00:24:36.050 --> 00:24:36.970
are limits.

00:24:36.970 --> 00:24:39.540
So if we consider lithium,
potassium, and sodium, they're

00:24:39.540 --> 00:24:42.690
all together in the same group
on the periodic table, knowing

