00:29:05.210 --> 00:29:09.000
So let's go to some actual real
examples, which might

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:10.750
come more in handy
for this class.

00:29:10.750 --> 00:29:13.310
So it's going to keep in mind
the limitations, so let's

00:29:13.310 --> 00:29:17.190
start off with talking about
ionization energy.

00:29:17.190 --> 00:29:19.410
Now this is a good place to
start, because we are very

00:29:19.410 --> 00:29:21.560
familiar with ionization energy,
we've been talking

00:29:21.560 --> 00:29:24.250
about it in a lot of different
forms for quite a while --

00:29:24.250 --> 00:29:28.220
it's that minimum energy
required to remove an electron

00:29:28.220 --> 00:29:29.310
from an atom.

00:29:29.310 --> 00:29:32.720
And specifically, when we talk
about ionization energy, it's

00:29:32.720 --> 00:29:34.810
assumed that what we mean
is actually the

00:29:34.810 --> 00:29:36.780
first ionization energy.

00:29:36.780 --> 00:29:39.310
So, you can imagine, we could
talk about any of the

00:29:39.310 --> 00:29:41.860
different electrons, or we could
talk about taking out an

00:29:41.860 --> 00:29:43.400
electron and taking out
second electron.

00:29:43.400 --> 00:29:47.690
Whenever you hear the term
ionization energy, make sure

00:29:47.690 --> 00:29:50.210
you keep in mind that unless
we say otherwise, we're

00:29:50.210 --> 00:29:53.040
talking about that first
ionization energy.

00:29:53.040 --> 00:29:55.490
And we know what that's equal
to, this is something we've

00:29:55.490 --> 00:29:58.880
been over and over, ionization
energy is simply equal to the

00:29:58.880 --> 00:30:00.840
negative of the binding
energy.

00:30:00.840 --> 00:30:04.390
So negative e, which is sub n l,
because it's a function of

00:30:04.390 --> 00:30:08.950
n and l in terms of
quantum numbers.

00:30:08.950 --> 00:30:12.730
So, let's think about kind of
differentiating, however,

00:30:12.730 --> 00:30:15.830
between first ionization energy
or just ionization

00:30:15.830 --> 00:30:18.960
energy, and other types such as
second or third ionization

00:30:18.960 --> 00:30:22.100
energy, and let's take boron
as an example here.

00:30:22.100 --> 00:30:24.510
So, if we want to think about
what the first ionization

00:30:24.510 --> 00:30:27.360
energy is of boron, what you
want to do is write out the

00:30:27.360 --> 00:30:29.490
electron configuration, because
then you can think

00:30:29.490 --> 00:30:32.070
about where it is that the
electron's coming out of.

00:30:32.070 --> 00:30:34.900
The electron's going to come out
of that highest occupied

00:30:34.900 --> 00:30:37.340
atomic orbital, that one that's
the highest in energy,

00:30:37.340 --> 00:30:39.730
because that's going to be the
at least amount of energy it

00:30:39.730 --> 00:30:41.120
needs to eject something.

00:30:41.120 --> 00:30:45.750
So what we'll end up with is
boron plus, 1 s 2, 2 s 2, and

00:30:45.750 --> 00:30:49.450
what we say is the delta energy
or the change in energy

00:30:49.450 --> 00:30:52.570
as the same thing as saying
the energy of the products

00:30:52.570 --> 00:30:55.210
minus the energy of our reactant
here, and we just

00:30:55.210 --> 00:30:57.310
call that the ionization energy
-- that's how much

00:30:57.310 --> 00:31:00.660
energy we have to put into the
system to eject an electron.

00:31:00.660 --> 00:31:03.560
And again, this is just the
negative, the binding energy,

00:31:03.560 --> 00:31:07.920
when we're talking about
the 2 p orbital.

00:31:07.920 --> 00:31:11.200
So, this is first ionization
energy, let's think about

00:31:11.200 --> 00:31:13.310
second ionization energy.

00:31:13.310 --> 00:31:16.040
So, second ionization energy
simply means you've already

00:31:16.040 --> 00:31:19.110
taken one electron out, now how
much energy does it take

00:31:19.110 --> 00:31:21.180
for you to take a second
electron out.

00:31:21.180 --> 00:31:24.210
So in the case of boron here,
what we're starting with is

00:31:24.210 --> 00:31:29.080
the ion, boron 1 s 2, 2 s 2,
and now we're going to pull

00:31:29.080 --> 00:31:30.850
one more electron out.

00:31:30.850 --> 00:31:34.570
The highest occupied orbital
is now the 2 s orbital, so

00:31:34.570 --> 00:31:39.470
we're going to end up with boron
2 plus 1 s 2, 2 s 1,

00:31:39.470 --> 00:31:42.410
plus the electron coming
out of there.

00:31:42.410 --> 00:31:45.490
And what we say when we talk
about the delta energy is that

00:31:45.490 --> 00:31:49.840
this is going to be equal to i
e 2, or the second ionization

00:31:49.840 --> 00:31:53.510
energy, or we could say the
negative of the binding energy

00:31:53.510 --> 00:31:58.400
of a 2 s electron in b plus. so
it's important to note that

00:31:58.400 --> 00:32:01.190
it's not in b, now we're talking
about b plus, because

00:32:01.190 --> 00:32:04.130
we've already taken an
electron out here.

00:32:04.130 --> 00:32:06.340
So, similarly if we start
talking about our third

00:32:06.340 --> 00:32:09.930
ionization energy, this is going
to be going from b plus

00:32:09.930 --> 00:32:12.690
2, to 1 s 2, 2 s 1.

00:32:12.690 --> 00:32:15.320
Now we're going to pull that
second electron out of the 2

00:32:15.320 --> 00:32:19.160
s, so we end up with boron
plus 3, and then the

00:32:19.160 --> 00:32:24.670
configuration is just 1 s 2,
plus our extra electron here.

00:32:24.670 --> 00:32:28.040
So, what we call this is the
third ionization energy, or

00:32:28.040 --> 00:32:30.770
the negative of the binding
energy, again of the 2 s

00:32:30.770 --> 00:32:35.850
orbital, but now it's in boron
plus 2 to we're starting with.

00:32:35.850 --> 00:32:38.830
So, this raises kind of an
interesting question in terms

00:32:38.830 --> 00:32:41.800
of what the difference is
between these two cases, and

00:32:41.800 --> 00:32:45.150
we're talking about
numbers of energy.

00:32:45.150 --> 00:32:48.930
So let's address this by
considering another example,

00:32:48.930 --> 00:32:51.830
which should clarify what the
difference is between these

00:32:51.830 --> 00:32:52.820
ionization energies.

00:32:52.820 --> 00:32:55.730
So let's think about the energy
required now to remove

00:32:55.730 --> 00:32:58.920
a 2 s electron, let's say we're
removing it from boron

00:32:58.920 --> 00:33:01.340
plus 1 versus neutral boron.

00:33:01.340 --> 00:33:06.050
So, in the case of boron plus
1, what we are starting with

00:33:06.050 --> 00:33:10.700
is the ion, so we're starting
with a 2 s electron, and then

00:33:10.700 --> 00:33:13.160
we're going to 2 s 1 here.

00:33:13.160 --> 00:33:16.800
And what we call the binding
energy is negative 2 s in b

00:33:16.800 --> 00:33:19.670
plus -- this is what we
saw on the last slide.

00:33:19.670 --> 00:33:22.695
And the second case here looks
a lot more like what we saw

00:33:22.695 --> 00:33:25.780
when we were talking about
photoelectron spectroscopy,

00:33:25.780 --> 00:33:28.610
because here we want to remove
a 2 s electron, but it's

00:33:28.610 --> 00:33:32.070
actually not the highest
occupied orbital, so that's

00:33:32.070 --> 00:33:34.140
not the one that would naturally
come out first, but

00:33:34.140 --> 00:33:36.160
let's say we're hitting it
with high energy light

00:33:36.160 --> 00:33:38.800
sufficient to knock out all the
different electrons, and

00:33:38.800 --> 00:33:41.810
one that we end up knocking
out is this 2 s here.

00:33:41.810 --> 00:33:45.160
So if we think about what that
delta energy is, we call that

00:33:45.160 --> 00:33:48.490
the ionization of the 2 s,
that's different from saying

00:33:48.490 --> 00:33:50.290
second ionization energy.

00:33:50.290 --> 00:33:52.580
And that's going to be equal
to the negative the binding

00:33:52.580 --> 00:33:57.020
energy of 2 s in b,
in neutral boron.

00:33:57.020 --> 00:34:01.100
So, my question to you is are
these two energies equal?

00:34:01.100 --> 00:34:02.290
No.

00:34:02.290 --> 00:34:03.730
All right, good answer.

00:34:03.730 --> 00:34:06.660
So, we can think about why is
it that these are not equal.

00:34:06.660 --> 00:34:08.580
In both cases we're
taking an electron

00:34:08.580 --> 00:34:11.130
out of the 2 s orbital.

00:34:11.130 --> 00:34:14.210
And it turns out that if we're
talking about a 2 s orbital in

00:34:14.210 --> 00:34:18.310
an ion, that means it doesn't
have as many electrons in it,

00:34:18.310 --> 00:34:20.410
so what we're going to see
is less sheilding.

00:34:20.410 --> 00:34:23.550
There are fewer electrons around
to shield some of that

00:34:23.550 --> 00:34:24.700
nuclear charge.

00:34:24.700 --> 00:34:27.660
So what we're going to see is
less sheilding, which means

00:34:27.660 --> 00:34:31.680
that it will actually feel
a higher z effective.

00:34:31.680 --> 00:34:35.410
So even though they're both 2 s
electrons, in one case it's

00:34:35.410 --> 00:34:38.300
going to think its feeling more
pull from the nucleus,

00:34:38.300 --> 00:34:41.430
and it, in fact, will be, than
in the other case, and if its

00:34:41.430 --> 00:34:44.090
feeling a higher z effective,
then it's actually going to

00:34:44.090 --> 00:34:46.820
require more energy to remove
that electron, right, it's

00:34:46.820 --> 00:34:49.480
being pulled in closer and more
tightly to the nucleus,

00:34:49.480 --> 00:34:52.310
you have to put in more energy
to rip it away from that very

00:34:52.310 --> 00:34:54.730
close interaction.

00:34:54.730 --> 00:34:57.380
So, that's the difference in
thinking about different types

00:34:57.380 --> 00:35:00.550
of ionization energy, so it can
get a little bit confusing

00:35:00.550 --> 00:35:02.620
with terminology if you're
just looking at something

00:35:02.620 --> 00:35:04.670
quickly, so make sure you look
really carefully about what

00:35:04.670 --> 00:35:05.460
we're discussing here.

00:35:05.460 --> 00:35:08.560
If you see a problem that asks
you, for example, the third

00:35:08.560 --> 00:35:11.710
ionization energy versus taking
a second electron out

00:35:11.710 --> 00:35:14.740
of the 2 s in a photoelectron
spectroscopy experiment, those

00:35:14.740 --> 00:35:17.480
are two very different things.

00:35:17.480 --> 00:35:20.200
So, let's make sure everyone
kind of has this down, let's

00:35:20.200 --> 00:35:25.030
do another clicker
question here.

00:35:25.030 --> 00:35:27.540
And in this case we're going to
look at silicone, and we'll

00:35:27.540 --> 00:35:31.120
say if you can point out to me
which requires the least

00:35:31.120 --> 00:35:32.310
amount of energy.

00:35:32.310 --> 00:35:35.380
So, which has the smallest
energy that you have to put in

00:35:35.380 --> 00:35:37.290
in order to eject
this electron?

00:35:37.290 --> 00:35:40.970
Will it be if you take a 3
s electron from neutral

00:35:40.970 --> 00:35:44.390
silicone, if you take a 3 p
electron from the neutral

00:35:44.390 --> 00:35:48.590
atom, or if you take
a 3 p from the ion?

00:35:48.590 --> 00:35:51.070
So this you should be able to
know pretty quickly, so let's

00:35:51.070 --> 00:36:05.280
just take 10 seconds here.

00:36:05.280 --> 00:36:05.950
All right, great.

00:36:05.950 --> 00:36:10.580
So most of you see that, in
fact, the energy that's going

00:36:10.580 --> 00:36:14.080
to be the least that we need to
put in is in case 2 here.

00:36:14.080 --> 00:36:16.950
Let's compare case 2 and 3,
since this where some people

00:36:16.950 --> 00:36:18.750
seem to have gotten confused.

00:36:18.750 --> 00:36:22.390
In case 2, we're taking it out
of -- oh, it's kind of hard to

00:36:22.390 --> 00:36:26.010
compare case 2 and 3 when
we can't see it anymore.

00:36:26.010 --> 00:36:32.140
In case 2, we're taking the 3
p out of the neutral atom,

00:36:32.140 --> 00:36:35.180
whereas in case 3, we're taking
it out of the ion.

00:36:35.180 --> 00:36:38.260
Remember in the ion, we're going
to have less electrons

00:36:38.260 --> 00:36:42.400
around to counteract the
pull from the nucleus.

00:36:42.400 --> 00:36:46.100
So we're going to feel a higher
z effective in the case

00:36:46.100 --> 00:36:48.860
of the ion compared to
the neutral atom.

00:36:48.860 --> 00:36:50.800
If we have a higher z effective,
it's pulled in

00:36:50.800 --> 00:36:53.670
tighter, we have to put in more
energy in order to eject

00:36:53.670 --> 00:36:56.220
an electron, so it turns out
that that's why case 2 is

00:36:56.220 --> 00:36:59.000
actually the lowest energy
that we need to put in.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:03.600
The z effective is lower, so we
have to put less energy in

00:37:03.600 --> 00:37:07.030
to get an ion out.

00:37:07.030 --> 00:37:10.990
So, let's take a look at this in
terms of periodic trends --

00:37:10.990 --> 00:37:14.150
that's our topic here, we're
talking about periodic trends.

00:37:14.150 --> 00:37:17.100
So as we go across the row,
and this is my beautiful

00:37:17.100 --> 00:37:19.050
picture of a periodic
table here.

00:37:19.050 --> 00:37:21.850
As we go across the row what
happens is that the ionization

00:37:21.850 --> 00:37:25.240
energy actually increases, and
we can think about logically

00:37:25.240 --> 00:37:27.540
why it is that that's
happening.

00:37:27.540 --> 00:37:31.020
As we go across the row, what we
have happening is that the

00:37:31.020 --> 00:37:32.710
z or the atomic charge --

00:37:32.710 --> 00:37:34.300
I'm not talking about z
effective here, I'm just

00:37:34.300 --> 00:37:37.960
talking about z -- the z is
increasing as we go across a

00:37:37.960 --> 00:37:39.800
row, that's easy to see.

00:37:39.800 --> 00:37:42.330
But we're still in the same
shell, so we still have the

00:37:42.330 --> 00:37:45.920
same n value as we go all the
way across a row in the

00:37:45.920 --> 00:37:47.260
periodic table.

00:37:47.260 --> 00:37:50.380
So, in general what we're going
to see is that what

00:37:50.380 --> 00:37:53.660
happens to z effective if we
have z increasing but we're in

00:37:53.660 --> 00:37:56.150
the same shell here.

00:37:56.150 --> 00:38:01.220
Would it increase or decrease
z effective?

00:38:01.220 --> 00:38:01.570
All right.

00:38:01.570 --> 00:38:04.140
Kind of mixed thoughts here.

00:38:04.140 --> 00:38:07.020
So it turns out that it
increases, and the reason is

00:38:07.020 --> 00:38:10.230
because the predominant thing
that's going on here is that z

00:38:10.230 --> 00:38:11.330
is increasing.

00:38:11.330 --> 00:38:13.970
So the z is increasing, and
what goes along with it is

00:38:13.970 --> 00:38:16.840
that the z effective is
increasing, because it turns

00:38:16.840 --> 00:38:19.430
out that while we're in the same
n, even though we know

00:38:19.430 --> 00:38:22.420
that energy depends on both the
n and the l in terms of

00:38:22.420 --> 00:38:25.390
quantum numbers, while we're
in the same n, the distance

00:38:25.390 --> 00:38:27.280
from the nucleus, it's
pretty close,

00:38:27.280 --> 00:38:28.850
it's not hugely different.

00:38:28.850 --> 00:38:30.850
So the factor that predominates
is that we're

00:38:30.850 --> 00:38:32.300
actually increasing z.

00:38:32.300 --> 00:38:34.680
That's why we see z effective
increase, and that's why we

00:38:34.680 --> 00:38:37.160
see ionization energy
increase.

00:38:37.160 --> 00:38:40.770
As we go down a column, what
happens is that the ionization

00:38:40.770 --> 00:38:42.040
energy decreases.

00:38:42.040 --> 00:38:45.220
We can also think about this
in terms of z effective.

00:38:45.220 --> 00:38:48.450
This is because even though z,
the atomic number is still

00:38:48.450 --> 00:38:51.300
increasing, we are also
getting further

00:38:51.300 --> 00:38:52.160
away from the nucleus.

00:38:52.160 --> 00:38:55.030
So, remember when we talk about
Coulomb force, what's

00:38:55.030 --> 00:38:57.750
holding the nucleus and the
electron together, there's 2

00:38:57.750 --> 00:38:58.890
things we need to think about.

00:38:58.890 --> 00:39:02.110
The first is this the z
effective, or how much charge

00:39:02.110 --> 00:39:05.130
is actually in the nucleus
that's felt, or the I guess we

00:39:05.130 --> 00:39:08.510
would say the z, how much the
charge is on the nucleus that

00:39:08.510 --> 00:39:09.870
holds it close together.

00:39:09.870 --> 00:39:11.970
But the second factor
is how far away we

00:39:11.970 --> 00:39:12.810
are from the nucleus.

00:39:12.810 --> 00:39:15.500
So, if we're really close to
the nucleus, that's when z

00:39:15.500 --> 00:39:18.410
effective is high, but if we
get really far away, then z

00:39:18.410 --> 00:39:20.590
effective is going to get low,
because even though we have

00:39:20.590 --> 00:39:22.640
the same charge in the
nucleus, the z

00:39:22.640 --> 00:39:23.670
effective gets lower.

00:39:23.670 --> 00:39:26.460
So this is not even thinking
about the other electron

00:39:26.460 --> 00:39:29.540
shielding, just if we think of
the fact, all we need to think

00:39:29.540 --> 00:39:33.030
about is that the effect of
going to a further away n

00:39:33.030 --> 00:39:36.170
actually dominates as we
go down the table.

00:39:36.170 --> 00:39:38.980
We're getting further away from
the nucleus because we're

00:39:38.980 --> 00:39:42.070
jumping, for example, from the
n equals 2 to the n equals 3

00:39:42.070 --> 00:39:45.030
shell, or from the n equals
3 to the n equals 4 shell.

00:39:45.030 --> 00:39:47.270
And when you're switching n's,
you're actually getting quite

00:39:47.270 --> 00:39:48.520
a bit farther away.

00:39:48.520 --> 00:39:50.980
That's why in the earlier models
of the atom, they're

00:39:50.980 --> 00:39:54.080
not horrible to sometimes think
about just each n value

00:39:54.080 --> 00:39:55.600
as a little ring around.

00:39:55.600 --> 00:39:58.530
It's not complete and it's not
accurate, but it's OK to kind

00:39:58.530 --> 00:40:00.840
of think of it in terms of how
far we're getting away from

00:40:00.840 --> 00:40:01.890
the nucleus.

00:40:01.890 --> 00:40:04.600
So, as we go down a column, we
see ionization energy's going

00:40:04.600 --> 00:40:06.850
to decrease.

00:40:06.850 --> 00:40:09.440
So, this means we have the
general trends down, so we

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:12.950
should be able to look at actual
atoms in our periodic

00:40:12.950 --> 00:40:14.580
table and graph them
and see that they

00:40:14.580 --> 00:40:16.040
match up with our trends.

00:40:16.040 --> 00:40:19.840
So here we have that graphed
here, we have atomic number z

00:40:19.840 --> 00:40:23.720
graphed against ionization
energy, so, let's fill in what

00:40:23.720 --> 00:40:27.080
the actual atoms are here, and
we can see in general, yes,

00:40:27.080 --> 00:40:28.260
we're following the trend.

00:40:28.260 --> 00:40:32.350
For row one, we're increasing,
as we should, across the row.

00:40:32.350 --> 00:40:34.550
Let's look at row two also.

00:40:34.550 --> 00:40:36.800
Well, we're generally increasing
here, we'll talk

00:40:36.800 --> 00:40:38.180
about that more in a minute.

00:40:38.180 --> 00:40:41.630
And also in a row three, yeah,
we're generally increasing,

00:40:41.630 --> 00:40:43.190
there's some glitches
here, but the

00:40:43.190 --> 00:40:45.320
general trend holds true.

00:40:45.320 --> 00:40:48.710
Similarly we see as we go down
the table, so as we're going

00:40:48.710 --> 00:40:52.780
from one row to the next row,
so, for example, between

00:40:52.780 --> 00:40:56.300
helium and lithium, we see a
drop; the same with neon to

00:40:56.300 --> 00:40:58.270
sodium, we see a drop here.

00:40:58.270 --> 00:41:00.660
So it looks like we're generally
following our trend,

00:41:00.660 --> 00:41:02.150
that's a good thing.

00:41:02.150 --> 00:41:05.720
But hopefully, you will not be
satisfied to just make a

00:41:05.720 --> 00:41:09.280
general statement here when
we do have these glitches.

00:41:09.280 --> 00:41:11.930
So you can see, for example, we
have several places where

00:41:11.930 --> 00:41:15.220
instead of going up as we go
across the row, we actually go

00:41:15.220 --> 00:41:17.460
down in ionization energy
a little bit.

00:41:17.460 --> 00:41:21.620
So between b e, and b, between
n and o, magesium and

00:41:21.620 --> 00:41:25.170
aluminum, and then phosphorous
and sulfur, what we see here

00:41:25.170 --> 00:41:27.700
is that we're kind of going
down, or quite specifically,

00:41:27.700 --> 00:41:29.250
we are going down.

00:41:29.250 --> 00:41:31.780
So, let's take a look at one of
these rows in more detail

00:41:31.780 --> 00:41:34.810
to think about why this might be
happening, and it turns out

00:41:34.810 --> 00:41:38.680
the reason that these glitches
occur are because the sub

00:41:38.680 --> 00:41:42.660
shell structure predominates
in certain instances, and

00:41:42.660 --> 00:41:44.930
that's where these glitches
take place.

00:41:44.930 --> 00:41:48.600
So I've sort of just spread out
what we have as the second

00:41:48.600 --> 00:41:52.800
row here, graphed against
the ionization energy.

00:41:52.800 --> 00:41:54.170
So, let's consider specifically
where these

00:41:54.170 --> 00:41:55.540
glitches are taking place.

00:41:55.540 --> 00:41:58.300
So, let's look at the first
one between beryllium and

00:41:58.300 --> 00:42:00.900
boron here.

00:42:00.900 --> 00:42:04.600
And the glitch that doesn't
make sense just through

00:42:04.600 --> 00:42:07.500
periodic trends, is that it
turns out that the ionization

00:42:07.500 --> 00:42:11.100
energy of boron is actually
less than the ionization

00:42:11.100 --> 00:42:12.680
energy up beryllium.

00:42:12.680 --> 00:42:15.060
So I put the electron
configurations and actually

00:42:15.060 --> 00:42:18.080
drew it on an energy diagram
here, so we can actually think

00:42:18.080 --> 00:42:19.880
about why this might
be happening.

00:42:19.880 --> 00:42:23.910
So what is this, which element
did I chart here?

00:42:23.910 --> 00:42:28.930
Which one is that, the boron
or the beryllium?

00:42:28.930 --> 00:42:30.730
I couldn't tell what
you said, sorry.

00:42:30.730 --> 00:42:34.530
So, I'm going to assume that
was beryllium, and then it

00:42:34.530 --> 00:42:36.210
turns out that if that's
beryllium, the

00:42:36.210 --> 00:42:37.930
other one must be boron.

00:42:37.930 --> 00:42:41.360
So, we have beryllium in the
first case here, it has four

00:42:41.360 --> 00:42:43.630
electrons, that's how we
know it's beryllium,

00:42:43.630 --> 00:42:45.500
boron has five electrons.

00:42:45.500 --> 00:42:49.370
So, just looking at putting in
the electrons, filling up the

00:42:49.370 --> 00:42:53.190
energy diagram here, we should
be able to see a little bit

00:42:53.190 --> 00:42:54.430
why this is happening.

00:42:54.430 --> 00:42:57.780
And the reason is simply because
the energy that we

00:42:57.780 --> 00:43:02.510
gain in terms of moving up in z,
so from going to z equals 4

00:43:02.510 --> 00:43:06.160
to z equals 5, is actually
outweighed by the energy it

00:43:06.160 --> 00:43:09.250
takes to go into this new
shell, to go into

00:43:09.250 --> 00:43:10.410
this new sub shell.

00:43:10.410 --> 00:43:14.330
So to jump from the 2 s to the 2
p, takes more energy than we

00:43:14.330 --> 00:43:17.580
can actually compensate with
by increasing the pull from

00:43:17.580 --> 00:43:18.560
the nucleus.

00:43:18.560 --> 00:43:23.020
So, it turns out that in this
case, and any time that we see

00:43:23.020 --> 00:43:27.960
we're going from a 2 s to 2 p,
filling in of electrons, we

00:43:27.960 --> 00:43:29.350
actually see that little
bit of glitch

00:43:29.350 --> 00:43:31.030
in ionization energy.

00:43:31.030 --> 00:43:33.350
So it's shown here for the
second row, but it's actually

00:43:33.350 --> 00:43:35.280
also going to be true
for the third row.

00:43:35.280 --> 00:43:38.080
The same thing when you're going
from filling in the 2 s

00:43:38.080 --> 00:43:40.380
to putting that first electron
into the 2 p.

00:43:40.380 --> 00:43:42.850
So that explains one of our
glitches here, but we have

00:43:42.850 --> 00:43:46.120
another glitch, and that second
glitch comes between

00:43:46.120 --> 00:43:48.400
nitrogen and oxygen.

00:43:48.400 --> 00:43:50.010
So, these sound more different,
so I think I'll be

00:43:50.010 --> 00:43:51.000
able to distinguish.

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:56.630
Which element is shown here?

00:43:56.630 --> 00:43:57.290
Yeah, nitrogen.

00:43:57.290 --> 00:44:00.220
So, nitrogen is shown
here, we know that

00:44:00.220 --> 00:44:01.950
because it has 7 electrons.

00:44:01.950 --> 00:44:03.460
In this case, we're
talking about 8

00:44:03.460 --> 00:44:06.470
electrons, which is oxygen.

00:44:06.470 --> 00:44:08.690
So if we're comparing the
difference between these 2

00:44:08.690 --> 00:44:11.950
now, what you'll notice is that
in nitrogen we have all

00:44:11.950 --> 00:44:16.700
half-filled 2 p orbitals, and
now, once we move into oxygen,

00:44:16.700 --> 00:44:19.340
we actually have to add
1 more electron into

00:44:19.340 --> 00:44:20.760
1 of the 2 p orbitals.

00:44:20.760 --> 00:44:23.050
There's no more 2 p orbitals to
put it into, so we're going

00:44:23.050 --> 00:44:24.540
to actually have to double up.

00:44:24.540 --> 00:44:27.570
So now we're putting 2 electrons
into the same p

00:44:27.570 --> 00:44:29.670
orbital, that's not a problem,
we can do it, it's not a huge

00:44:29.670 --> 00:44:30.980
energy cost to do that.

00:44:30.980 --> 00:44:33.900
But actually there is a little
bit of an energy cost into

00:44:33.900 --> 00:44:36.670
doubling up into a single
orbital, because, of course,

00:44:36.670 --> 00:44:40.380
it takes energy when you
create more electron

00:44:40.380 --> 00:44:42.820
repulsion, that's not something
we want to do, but

00:44:42.820 --> 00:44:45.810
we have to do it here, and it
turns out that that effect

00:44:45.810 --> 00:44:48.640
predominates over, again, the
energy that we gain by

00:44:48.640 --> 00:44:51.160
increasing the atomic
number by one.

00:44:51.160 --> 00:44:54.480
So, our two glitches we see when
we go from the 2 p, or

00:44:54.480 --> 00:44:57.500
from 2 s to start filling the
2 p, and then we also get

00:44:57.500 --> 00:45:00.380
another glitch when we've
half-filled the 2 p, and now

00:45:00.380 --> 00:45:02.170
we're adding and having
to double up in

00:45:02.170 --> 00:45:03.550
one of those p orbitals.

00:45:03.550 --> 00:45:05.510
Again, we see the same
effect as we go into

00:45:05.510 --> 00:45:09.410
different rows as well.

00:45:09.410 --> 00:45:13.440
So let's talk about another
periodic trend, this one is

00:45:13.440 --> 00:45:14.660
called electron affinity.

00:45:14.660 --> 00:45:19.140
Electron affinity is actually
the ability of an atom, or we

00:45:19.140 --> 00:45:21.880
could also talk about an
ion to gain electrons.

00:45:21.880 --> 00:45:24.590
So it's the affinity it has for
electrons, it's how much

00:45:24.590 --> 00:45:26.370
it likes to get an electron.

00:45:26.370 --> 00:45:30.320
We can write out what it is for
any certain atom or ion x,

00:45:30.320 --> 00:45:33.550
so it's just x plus an electron
gives us x minus.

00:45:33.550 --> 00:45:35.970
We have the minus because we're
adding a negative charge

00:45:35.970 --> 00:45:37.550
from the electron.

00:45:37.550 --> 00:45:40.780
So, basically any time we have
a really high positive number

00:45:40.780 --> 00:45:44.110
of electron affinity, it means
that that atom or ion really

00:45:44.110 --> 00:45:46.620
wants to gain another electron,
and it will be very

00:45:46.620 --> 00:45:48.690
stable and happy
if it does so.

00:45:48.690 --> 00:45:51.800
So let's look at an example
of chlorine here.

00:45:51.800 --> 00:45:54.950
So chlorine, if we talk about
it in terms of electron

00:45:54.950 --> 00:45:58.010
affinity, we would be writing
that we're actually gaining an

00:45:58.010 --> 00:46:01.230
electron here, and getting
the ion, c l minus.

00:46:01.230 --> 00:46:04.760
And the change in energy for
this reaction is negative 349

00:46:04.760 --> 00:46:07.490
kilojoules per mole.

00:46:07.490 --> 00:46:10.110
So if we have a negative change
in energy for any

00:46:10.110 --> 00:46:12.960
reaction as it's written, what
that actually means is we're

00:46:12.960 --> 00:46:15.990
giving off energy as the
reaction proceeds.

00:46:15.990 --> 00:46:19.640
So, in other words, this c l
minus is actually lower in

00:46:19.640 --> 00:46:21.500
energy than the reactants
were.

00:46:21.500 --> 00:46:23.500
So that's why we're giving
off extra energy.

00:46:23.500 --> 00:46:25.940
We saw a similar thing as we
saw electrons move from

00:46:25.940 --> 00:46:26.770
different levels.

00:46:26.770 --> 00:46:29.350
We can think of it in the same
type of way when we're talking

00:46:29.350 --> 00:46:31.720
about actual reactions
happening.

00:46:31.720 --> 00:46:34.930
So, if we have energy that's
released, would you say that

00:46:34.930 --> 00:46:38.270
the chlorine ion is more
or less stable than

00:46:38.270 --> 00:46:38.830
the chlorine atom?

00:46:38.830 --> 00:46:42.300
Who thinks it's more stable,
show of hands?

00:46:42.300 --> 00:46:45.260
All right, who thinks
it's less stable?

00:46:45.260 --> 00:46:46.450
Very good.

00:46:46.450 --> 00:46:48.660
So it turns out it is,
in fact, more stable.

00:46:48.660 --> 00:46:51.370
It's more stable because you
actually -- this happens

00:46:51.370 --> 00:46:54.610
spontaneously, you actually get
energy out of the reaction

00:46:54.610 --> 00:46:55.410
as this happens.

00:46:55.410 --> 00:46:57.510
And we haven't talked about
reactions at all yet, so you

00:46:57.510 --> 00:47:01.400
don't need to worry about the
specifics of that exactly, but

00:47:01.400 --> 00:47:03.830
just that if you have this
negative change in energy, you

00:47:03.830 --> 00:47:07.430
have a more stable product
than you do reactant.

00:47:07.430 --> 00:47:11.150
So, we were talking, however,
about energy in terms of

00:47:11.150 --> 00:47:14.040
electron affinity, so we can
actually relate electron

00:47:14.040 --> 00:47:17.470
affinity to any reaction by
saying if we have this

00:47:17.470 --> 00:47:20.310
reaction written as here where
we're gaining an electron, we

00:47:20.310 --> 00:47:23.110
say that electron affinity is
just equal to the negative of

00:47:23.110 --> 00:47:24.780
that change in energy.

00:47:24.780 --> 00:47:28.240
So, for example, for the
chlorine case, we would say

00:47:28.240 --> 00:47:32.090
that the electron affinity for
chlorine is actually positive

00:47:32.090 --> 00:47:35.120
349 kilojoules per mole.

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:37.980
That's a very large number,
it's all relative, so you

00:47:37.980 --> 00:47:39.990
don't necessarily know it's
large without me telling you

00:47:39.990 --> 00:47:43.690
or giving you other ions to
compare to, but chlorine does

00:47:43.690 --> 00:47:46.670
have a very large affinity,
meaning it's really likes

00:47:46.670 --> 00:47:50.170
getting an electron and becoming
a chlorine ion.

00:47:50.170 --> 00:47:53.020
One major difference between
electron affinity and

00:47:53.020 --> 00:47:56.010
ionization energy is that when
we talked about ionization

00:47:56.010 --> 00:47:58.230
energy, remember ionization
energy

00:47:58.230 --> 00:47:59.790
always has to be positive.

00:47:59.790 --> 00:48:01.230
We will never have a case where

00:48:01.230 --> 00:48:03.410
ionization energy is negative.

00:48:03.410 --> 00:48:06.200
Electron affinity, however, can
be either negative or it

00:48:06.200 --> 00:48:07.540
can be positive.

00:48:07.540 --> 00:48:09.160
So let's look at a
case where it's

00:48:09.160 --> 00:48:10.350
actually going to be negative.

00:48:10.350 --> 00:48:12.610
So, if we took the case of
nitrogen, if we add an

00:48:12.610 --> 00:48:15.750
electron to nitrogen and go to
n minus, we find that the

00:48:15.750 --> 00:48:18.600
change in energy is 7
kilojoules per mole.

00:48:18.600 --> 00:48:22.310
This means in order to do that
we actually have to put 7

00:48:22.310 --> 00:48:24.320
kilojoules per mole
of energy into the

00:48:24.320 --> 00:48:26.000
reaction to make it happen.

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:28.450
So this is not going to be a
favorable process, we're going

00:48:28.450 --> 00:48:31.620
to find that the electron
affinity is actually a

00:48:31.620 --> 00:48:34.590
negative 7 kilojoules per
mole for nitrogen.

00:48:34.590 --> 00:48:38.240
So this means nitrogen has low
electron affinity, it doesn't

00:48:38.240 --> 00:48:41.710
actually want to gain
an electron.

00:48:41.710 --> 00:48:45.440
So, that also tells us that the
n minus ion is less stable

00:48:45.440 --> 00:48:47.950
than the neutral atom itself.

00:48:47.950 --> 00:48:50.930
So, we can think about trends in
electron affinity just like

00:48:50.930 --> 00:48:53.180
we did for ionization energy,
and what we see

00:48:53.180 --> 00:48:54.510
is a similar trend.

00:48:54.510 --> 00:48:57.760
Electron affinity increases as
we go across a row in the

00:48:57.760 --> 00:49:00.500
periodic table, and
it decreases as

00:49:00.500 --> 00:49:02.320
we go down a column.

00:49:02.320 --> 00:49:05.090
I left out the noble gases here
because they do something

00:49:05.090 --> 00:49:07.240
a little bit special, and
actually, I'm going to give

00:49:07.240 --> 00:49:10.320
you one last clicker question
today to see if you can tell

00:49:10.320 --> 00:49:12.480
me what you think
noble gases do.

00:49:12.480 --> 00:49:14.300
To answer this question you
just really want to think

00:49:14.300 --> 00:49:16.020
about what does electron
affinity means.

00:49:16.020 --> 00:49:18.600
It means how much a certain
atom actually

00:49:18.600 --> 00:49:21.370
wants to get an electron.

00:49:21.370 --> 00:49:23.880
So do you think noble gases
would have a high positive

00:49:23.880 --> 00:49:25.910
electron affinity, a
low positive, or

00:49:25.910 --> 00:49:26.700
negative electron affinity?

00:49:26.700 --> 00:49:40.160
So, let's take 10
seconds on that.

00:49:40.160 --> 00:49:40.480
All right.

00:49:40.480 --> 00:49:40.850
Great.

00:49:40.850 --> 00:49:43.800
So most of you recognize, if we
switch back to the notes,

00:49:43.800 --> 00:49:46.150
that they do have a negative
electron affinity.

00:49:46.150 --> 00:49:48.430
This should make sense to you,
because they don't, in fact,

00:49:48.430 --> 00:49:51.450
want to gain another electron,
because that would mean that

00:49:51.450 --> 00:49:54.750
electron would have to go into a
new value of n, a new shell,

00:49:54.750 --> 00:49:56.350
and that's really going
to increase the

00:49:56.350 --> 00:49:58.220
energy of the system.

00:49:58.220 --> 00:50:00.910
So they'd much rather just stay
the way they are and not

00:50:00.910 --> 00:50:04.400
have another electron come on,
and it turns out that halogens

00:50:04.400 --> 00:50:06.570
have the highest electron
affinities.

